he input spec says: \\n110ns  1       1       1       0\\n115ns  0       0       1       1\\n120ns  0       1       1       1\\n\\nThis means at 110ns (posedge), a=1, p=1, q=0. Between 110ns and 115ns (negedge), p and q change? That\'s only possible if they are combinational and depend on \'a\' or if the state changes on negedge. But the clock is 10ns period. 110ns is posedge, 115ns is negedge.\\n\\nWait, if p and q are combinational, they can change at 115ns if \'a\' changes at 115ns. But \'a\' is 0 at 115ns and was 0 at 105ns. So \'a\' didn\'t change at 115ns. \\nThis implies the state changed at 115ns (negedge).\\n\\nLet\'s re-examine the waveform carefully.\\nAt 110ns: clock=1, a=1, p=1, q=0.\\nAt 115ns: clock=0, a=0, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 120ns: clock=0, a=1, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 145ns: clock=1, a=0, p=0, q=1.\\nAt 165ns: clock=1, a=1, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 170ns: clock=1, a=0, p=0, q=1.\\nAt 175ns: clock=0, a=1, p=0, q=0.\\n\\nIf state changes on negedge:\\nAt 115ns (negedge), q becomes 1. This happened when a was 0 and p was 1? No, p was 1 at 110ns and remains 1 at 115ns.\\n\\nLet\'s try a different approach. What if the state machine is:\\nState 0 (Idle): p=0, q=0. Transition to State 1 if a=1.\\nState 1 (Detecting): p=a, q=0. Transition to State 2 if a=1 AND we have seen a=1 previously? \\nActually, looking at 90, 100, 110: p=1 when a=1. This looks like p = a (with some delay or state).\\nAt 110ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. The next step is q=1. \\nIt looks like q becomes 1 after three consecutive (or non-consecutive?) a=1 pulses.\\n\\nLet\'s look at the transitions for q:\\n- q=0 until 115ns (negedge).\\n- q=1 from 115ns to 175ns.\\n- q=0 after 175ns (negedge).\\n\\nWhen does q become 1? At 115ns, which is the negedge after a sequence of a=1.\\nSequence of a at posedges: 90(a=1), 100(a=1), 110(a=1). That\'s three \'a\'s.\\nWhen does q become 0? At 175ns (negedge). \\nSequence of a at posedges after q=1: 165(a=1), 170(a=0).\\nWait, at 175ns (negedge), a=1, but p and q both become 0.\\n\\nLet\'s try to implement a state machine that tracks the number of \'a\' pulses.\\nState 0: q=0, p=0. If a=1, goto State 1.\\nState 1: q=0, p=a. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 0.\\nState 2: q=0, p=a. If a=1, goto State 3. If a=0, goto State 1.\\nState 3: q=1, p=a. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 4? No.\\n\\nActually, let\'s look at the output p again. \\nAt 115ns, p=1 even though a=0. \\nAt 120ns, a=1, p=1. \\nAt 145ns, a=0, p=0. \\nAt 165ns, a=1, p=1.\\nAt 170ns, a=0, p=0.\\nAt 175ns, a=1, p=0. (This is a mismatch with p=a).\\n\\nThis suggests p and q are driven by the state, and the state changes on negedge or posedge.\\nGiven the waveform, let\'s try to use a state machine that transitions on both edges or just use a simpler logic.\\nActually, many of these behaviors can be described by a state machine that transitions on posedge and has outputs that depend on the current state and \'a\'.\\n\\nLet\'s re-trace q: \\nIt stays 0 while a is being pulsed. After the 3rd pulse (at 110ns), at the next negedge (115ns), q becomes 1.\\nIt stays 1 as long as a is pulsed or 0. \\nAt 170ns, a=0. At 175ns (negedge), q becomes 0. This is after a=0 at 170ns.\\n\\nLet\'s try this:\\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1, goto State 1.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 0.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1, goto State 3. If a=0, goto State 1.\\nState 3: p=a, q=1. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 4.\\nState 4: p=0, q=1. If a=1, goto State 0. If a=0, goto State 4.\\n\\nWait, let\'s check 175ns. At 170ns, a=0. If we are in State 4, q=1. At 175ns (negedge), q becomes 0. This would happen if the state transitions on negedge.\\n\\nLet\'s try a state machine that transitions on posedge and we\'ll see if we can match the negedge behavior.\\nIf the state machine transitions on posedge, we can\'t easily explain the 115ns negedge change unless the outputs are combinational and depend on \'a\', but \'a\' doesn\'t change at 115ns. \\nUnless... the state transition is on negedge.\\n\\nIf state transitions on negedge:\\n- 110ns: posedge, a=1, state stays in State 2.\\n- 115ns: negedge, a=0, state moves from State 2 to State 3.\\n- State 3: p=1, q=1. (Matches 115ns-130ns).\\n- 145ns: posedge, a=0, state stays in State 3.\\n- 165ns: posedge, a=1, state stays in State 3.\\n- 170ns: posedge, a=0, state stays in State 3.\\n- 175ns: negedge, a=1, state moves from State 3 to State 0.\\n- State 0: p=0, q=0. (Matches 180ns).\\n\\nThis looks promising! Let\'s refine the states with negedge transition:\\nState 0 (Idle): p=0, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 1.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 0.\\nState 1 (First pulse): p=a, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 2.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 0.\\nState 2 (Second pulse): p=a, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 3. \\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 1.\\nState 3 (Third pulse/q=1): p=1, q=1. (Wait, 115ns a=0, p=1, q=1, so p is 1).\\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 2.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 4?\\nState 4 (Resetting q): p=0, q=1. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 0.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 4.\\n\\nWait, let\'s check State 3 p value. At 115ns, a=0 and p=1. At 120ns, a=1 and p=1. So in State 3, p=1.\\nAt 145ns, a=0 and p=0. This means State 3 is not quite right. \\nAt 145ns, a=0, p=0, q=1. This matches State 4.\\nSo at 115ns (negedge), if a=0, we go to State 4. \\nState 4: p=a, q=1. \\nLet\'s check: 145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n165ns: a=1, p=1, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n170ns: a=0, p=0, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n175ns: negedge, a=1. If in State 4 and a=1, go to State 0. \\nState 0: p=0, q=0. (Matches 180ns).\\n\\nLet\'s re-verify State 2:\\nAt 110ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. (State 2).\\nAt 115ns, a=0, p=1, q=1. (State 4).\\nWait, if state transition is on negedge, at 115ns (negedge) a=0, so we move from State 2 to State 4.\\nState 2: p=1 (since a=1 at 110ns), q=0.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. \\nAt 115ns, a=0, so p=0? But the waveform says p=1 at 115ns. \\nThis means p is 1 at 115ns. This could be because p is combinational and uses the \'a\' from the previous state, or p=1 in State 4 as well.\\n\\nLet\'s look at 145ns again. a=0, p=0, q=1. If this is State 4, then p=a works.\\nBut at 115ns, a=0 and p=1. This is a contradiction if p=a in State 4.\\nUnless... the state at 115ns is State 3, where p=1.\\n\\nLet\'s try: \\nState 0: p=0, q=0. Negedge: if a=1 -> State 1, else State 0.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. Negedge: if a=1 -> State 2, else State 0.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. Negedge: if a=1 -> State 2, else State 3.\\nState 3: p=1, q=1. Negedge: if a=1 -> State 2, else State 4.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. Negedge: if a=1 -> State 0, else State 4.\\n\\nCheck 115ns: a=0, State 2 -> State 3. State 3 has p=1, q=1. (Matches 115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1).\\nCheck 145ns: a=0, State 3 -> State 4. State 4 has p=a, q=1. (Matches 145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1).\\nCheck 165ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 0? No, at 165ns, a=1, p=1, q=1. This matches State 4 (p=a=1).\\nCheck 170ns: a=0, State 4 -> State 4. (Matches 170ns: a=0, p=0, q=1).\\nCheck 175ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 0. State 0 has p=0, q=0. (Matches 180ns).\\n\\nThis seems to fit perfectly! The state transitions on negedge.\\n\\nFinal State Machine Plan (Negedge Transition):\\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1 -> State 1, else State 0.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 0.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 3.\\nState 3: p=1, q=1. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 4.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 0, else State 4.\\n\\nWait, one more check: 90ns, 100ns, 110ns. \\nAt 90ns (pos), a=1. At 95ns (negedge), a=0. \\nIf we transition on negedge, at 95ns, a=0, so State 1 -> State 0. \\nBut at 100ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. This means at 100ns we are in State 1.\\nSo at 95ns, if a=0, we should go to State 1? No, that doesn\'t make sense. \\nLet\'s re-trace the 90-110ns sequence.\\n90ns: a=1, p=1, q=0.\\n95ns: a=0, p=0, q=0.\\n100ns: a=1, p=1, q=0.\\n105ns: a=0, p=0, q=0.\\n110ns: a=1, p=1, q=0.\\n115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1.\\n\\nThis means the \'a\' pulses are not necessarily consecutive. \\nActually, at 95ns, a=0, and we are in State 1. At 100ns, a=1, we stay in State 1 or go to State 2? \\nIf we are in State 1, and a=0, we stay in State 1? \\nLet\'s try:\\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1 -> State 1, else State 0.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 1.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 3, else State 1.\\nState 3: p=1, q=1. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 4.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 0, else State 4.\\n\\nCheck 95ns: a=0, State 1 -> State 1. (Matches 95ns: a=0, p=0, q=0).\\nCheck 100ns: a=1, State 1 -> State 2. (Matches 100ns: a=1, p=1, q=0).\\nCheck 105ns: a=0, State 2 -> State 1. (Matches 105ns: a=0, p=0, q=0).\\nCheck 110ns: a=1, State 1 -> State 2. (Matches 110ns: a=1, p=1, q=0).\\nCheck 115ns: a=0, State 2 -> State 3. (Matches 115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1).\\nWait, if State 2 -> State 3 when a=0 at 115ns, then State 3 has p=1, q=1. \\nThis matches 115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1.\\nThen 145ns: a=0, State 3 -> State 4. State 4 has p=a, q=1. (Matches 145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1).\\nThen 165ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 0? No, 165ns: a=1, p=1, q=1. This matches State 4.\\n170ns: a=0, State 4 -> State 4. (Matches 170ns: a=0, p=0, q=1).\\n175ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 0. (Matches 180ns: p=0, q=0).\\n\\nPerfect! All transitions and outputs match the waveform.\\n\\nSummary of State Machine (Negedge transition):\\nState 0: p=0, q=0. a=1 -> State 1, a=0 -> State 0.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. a=1 -> State 2, a=0 -> State 1.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. a=1 -> State 3, a=0 -> State 1.\\nState 3: p=1, q=1. a=1 -> State 2, a=0 -> State 4.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. a=1 -> State 0, a=0 -> State 4.\\n\\nWait, one detail: In State 2, if a=1, it goes to State 3. In State 3, if a=1, it goes back to State 2. This allows for a sequence of a=1 to keep q=1.\\nLet\'s double check 110ns-115ns again.\\n110ns: a=1. At 115ns (negedge), a=0. \\nIf we were in State 2 at 110ns, and a=0 at 115ns, we go to State 3.\\nState 3: p=1, q=1. (Matches 115ns).\\n\\nOne more thing: The waveform shows p=1 at 110ns. In State 2, p=a. Since a=1 at 110ns, p=1. Correct.\\n\\nImplementation details:\\n- Use `always @(negedge clock)` for state transitions.\\n- Use `always @(*)` for combinational outputs.\\n- Initialize state in an `initial` block.\\n",\n    "action_input": {\n        "command": "replace_content_by_matching",\n        "args": {\n            "old_content": "    // Next state combinational logic\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        state_next = state;\\n        case (state)\\n            STATE_0: begin\\n                if (a) state_next = STATE_1;\\n                else    state_next = STATE_0;\\n            end\\n            STATE_1: begin\\n                if (a) state_next = STATE_1;\\n                else    state_next = STATE_2;\\n            end\\n            STATE_2: begin\\n                if (a) state_next = STATE_2;\\n                else    state_next = STATE_3;\\n            end\\n            STATE_3: begin\\n                if (a) state_next = STATE_0;\\n                else    state_next = STATE_3;\\n            end\\n            default: state_next = STATE_0;\\n        endcase\\n    end\\n\\n    // Output combinational logic\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        p = 1\'b0;\\n        q = 1\'b0;\\n        case (state)\\n            STATE_0: begin\\n                p = 1\'b0;\\n                q = 1\'b0;\\n            end\\n            STATE_1: begin\\n                p = a;\\n                q = 1\'b0;\\n            end\\n            STATE_2: begin\\n                p = 1\'b1;\\n                q = 1\'b1;\\n            end\\n            STATE_3: begin\\n                p = a;\\n                q = 1\'b1;\\n            end\\n        endcase\\n    end",\n            "new_content": "    // Sequential logic for state transition (on negedge)\\n    always @(negedge clock) begin\\n        case (state)\\n            STATE_0: state <= (a) ? STATE_1 : STATE_0;\\n            STATE_1: state <= (a) ? STATE_2 : STATE_1;\\n    