ifferent. \nActually, the most common thing in these problems is a state machine that transitions on posedge, and the negedge behavior is just because of how the testbench/waveform is presented.\n\nLet's try a posedge state machine with these states:\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1 -> State 1.\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 0.\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 3, else State 1.\nState 3: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 3, else State 4.\nState 4: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 0, else State 4.\n\nCheck: \n- 90ns: a=1, State 0 -> State 1. p=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 100ns: a=1, State 1 -> State 2. p=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 110ns: a=1, State 2 -> State 3. p=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 120ns: a=1, State 3 -> State 3. p=1, q=1. (Matches).\n- 145ns: a=0, State 3 -> State 4. p=0, q=1. (Matches).\n- 165ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 0. p=1, q=1. (Wait, if State 4 -> State 0, then p=a=1, q=1. Matches!).\n- 170ns: a=0, State 0 -> State 0. p=0, q=0. (Wait, 170ns waveform says q=1).\n\nLet's try: State 4: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 3, else State 4.\n- 165ns: a=1, State 4 -> State 3. p=1, q=1. (Matches).\n- 170ns: a=0, State 3 -> State 4. p=0, q=1. (Matches).\n- 175ns (negedge): a=1. If we transition on negedge, State 4 -> State 0. \n\nWait, the only way to get the negedge transition is to use `always @(negedge clock)`.\nLet's re-try the negedge state machine one more time, very carefully.\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1 -> State 1, else State 0.\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 1.\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1 -> State 3, else State 1.\nState 3: p=1, q=1. If a=1 -> State 2, else State 4. (Wait, 115ns a=0, State 2 -> State 3. 115ns is negedge. If a=0, State 2 -> State 3. State 3: p=1, q=1. Matches!).\nState 4: p=a, q=1. If a=1 -> State 0, else State 4.\n\nLet's re-trace 90ns-95ns with this:\n- 85ns (negedge): a=0. State 0 -> State 0. (Wait, if a=0, it stays 0. Then at 90ns, p=0. But waveform says p=1).\n- This means at 85ns (negedge), the state must have become State 1.\n- How can State 0 -> State 1 if a=0 at 85ns? \n- Maybe the transition is: If a=1 at POSEDGE, change state at NEXT NEGEDGE.\n\nLet's try that! (This is equivalent to a negedge-triggered state machine where the input is sampled at posedge).\n- 80ns: a=1. \n- 85ns (negedge): State becomes State 1. (p=a=0, q=0).\n- 90ns (posedge): a=1. \n- 95ns (negedge): State becomes State 2. (p=a=0, q=0). (Wait, still p=0 at 90ns).\n\nLet's look at the waveform again. 90ns: a=1, p=1, q=0. This is at a posedge.\nIf the state machine is posedge-triggered, and p, q are combinational:\n- 90ns: a=1, State 0 -> State 1. p=a=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 95ns: a=0, State 1 -> State 1. p=a=0, q=0. (Matches).\n- 100ns: a=1, State 1 -> State 2. p=a=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 105ns: a=0, State 2 -> State 1. p=a=0, q=0. (Matches).\n- 110ns: a=1, State 1 -> State 2. p=a=1, q=0. (Matches).\n- 115ns: a=0, State 2 -> State 3. (Wait, this is a negedge transition!).\n\nIs it possible the state transitions on both edges? \n- Posedge: if a=1, state++.\n- Negedge: if a=0, state++.\n\nLet's try: \n- 90ns (pos): a=1, State 0 -> State 1. (p=a=1, q=0).\n- 95ns (neg): a=0, State 1 -> State 2. (p=a=0, q=0).\n- 100ns (pos): a=1, State 2 -> State 3. (p=a=1, q=0).\n- 105ns (neg): a=0, State 3 -> State 4. (p=a=0, q=1).\n- 110ns (pos): a=1, State 4 -> State 3. (p=a=1, q=1).\n- 115ns (neg): a=0, State 3 -> State 4. (p=a=0, q=1). (Matches 115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1? No, p=0).\n\nOne last attempt at the logic: \nLooking at the waveform, p=1 whenever a=1, except at 175ns. And q=1 after three a=1s. \nWait, the 175ns mismatch: 170ns a=0, 175ns a=1. \nAt 175ns, p becomes 0 and q becomes 0. \nThis happens at a negedge.\nIf we use: \n- p = a;\n- q = (count of a pulses >= 3) && (no a=1 after q becomes 1? No).\n\nLet's use the most robust state machine that can match this: A state machine that transitions on both edges.\n- Posedge: if a=1, state = next_state_a1;\n- Negedge: if a=0, state = next_state_a0;\n\nLet's try to find the states:\n- 90ns: a=1, posedge, State 0 -> State 1. (p=1, q=0).\n- 95ns: a=0, negedge, State 1 -> State 1. (p=0, q=0).\n- 100ns: a=1, posedge, State 1 -> State 2. (p=1, q=0).\n- 105ns: a=0, negedge, State 2 -> State 2. (p=0, q=0).\n- 110ns: a=1, posedge, State 2 -> State 3. (p=1, q=0).\n- 115ns: a=0, negedge, State 3 -> State 4. (p=1, q=1). (So in State 3, p=1).\n- 120ns: a=1, posedge, State 4 -> State 4. (p=1, q=1).\n- 145ns: a=0, posedge, State 4 -> State 4. (p=0, q=1).\n- 165ns: a=1, posedge, State 4 -> State 4. (p=1, q=1).\n- 170ns: a=0, posedge, State 4 -> State 4. (p=0, q=1).\n- 175ns: a=1, negedge, State 4 -> State 0. (p=0, q=0).\n\nThis works! \nState 0: p=0, q=0. (Pos: a=1->S1, Neg: a=0->S0).\nState 1: p=a, q=0. (Pos: a=1->S2, Neg: a=0->S1).\nState 2: p=a, q=0. (Pos: a=1->S3, Neg: a=0->S2).\nState 3: p=1, q=0. (Pos: a=1->S3, Neg: a=0->S4).\nState 4: p=a, q=1. (Pos: a=1->S4, Neg: a=1->S0, Neg: a=0->S4). \nWait, State 4 negedge: if a=1, go to State 0. If a=0, stay in State 4.\n\nLet's refine State 3: In State 3, if a=1 at posedge, we stay in State 3. If a=0 at negedge, we go to State 4. \nAnd at 115ns, a=0, so State 3 -> State 4. In State 4, p=a. But at 115ns, a=0, so p=0. \nBut the waveform says p=1 at 115ns. \nThis means in State 4, p=1? No, 145ns a=0, p=0. \nThis means at 115ns, the state is State 3, and p=1. \nSo State 3 transition must be on posedge or negedge? \nIf State 3 is reached at 110ns (posedge), and it stays in State 3 until 115ns (negedge) where it transitions to State 4. \nIn State 3, p=1. In State 4, p=a. \nAt 115ns, a=0, so p transitions from 1 to 0. But the waveform says p=1. \nThis means the state transition at 115ns must be to a state where p=1. \nLet's try: State 3: p=1, q=1. \nState 3: (Pos: a=1->S3, Neg: a=0->S4). \nState 4: p=a, q=1. \nAt 115ns, a=0, State 3 -> State 4. p=a=0. Still p=0. \nUnless State 3 transition is on POSEDGE. \nIf State 3 transition is on posedge: at 110ns, a=1, State 2 -> State 3. p=1, q=0. \nAt 120ns, a=1, State 3 -> State 3. p=1, q=1. \nAt 145ns, a=0, State 3 -> State 4. p=0, q=1. \nThis matches! \n\nSo: \n- Posedge transitions: 0->1 (a=1), 1->2 (a=1), 2->3 (a=1), 3->4 (a=0), 4->0 (a=1).\n- Negedge transitions: 3->4 (a=0), 4->0 (a=1), 4->4 (a=0).\n\nWait, this is getting complicated. Let's simplify: \n- Posedge: S0->S1 (a=1), S1->S2 (a=1), S2->S3 (a=1), S3->S4 (a=0), S4->S0 (a=1).\n- Negedge: S3->S4 (a=0), S4->S0 (a=1), S4->S4 (a=0).\n\nLet's check: \n110ns: a=1, posedge, S2 -> S3. p=1, q=0. (Matches).\n115ns: a=0, negedge, S3 -> S4. p=a=0, q=1. (Wait, waveform says p=1 at 115ns). \nIf p=1 at 115ns, then at 115ns we are still in State 3. \nThis means the transition S3->S4 happens at 120ns (posedge)? No, 120ns is a=1. \n\nActually, the waveform is: \n110ns: a=1, p=1, q=0.\n115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1.\n120ns: a=1, p=1, q=1.\n125ns: a=0, p=1, q=1.\n130ns: a=1, p=1, q=1.\n145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1.\n\nThis means p=1 in State 3, and State 3 transition to State 4 happens at 145ns (posedge) when a=0. \nSo: \n- Posedge: S0->S1 (a=1), S1->S2 (a=1), S2->S3 (a=1), S3->S4 (a=0), S4->S0 (a=1).\n- Negedge: S3->S3 (a=0), S4->S4 (a=0), S4->S0 (a=1).\n\nCheck 115ns: a=0, negedge, S3 -> S3. p=1, q=1. (Matches!).\nCheck 145ns: a=0, posedge, S3 -> S4. p=a=0, q=1. (Matches!).\nCheck 165ns: a=1, posedge, S4 -> S0. p=a=1, q=1. (Matches!).\nCheck 170ns: a=0, posedge, S0 -> S0. p=0, q=0. (Wait, 170ns waveform says q=1).\n\nIf 170ns q=1, then at 170ns we are in State 4. \nSo S4 -> S4 on a=0 (posedge). And S4 -> S0 on a=1 (posedge).\n- 165ns: a=1, posedge, S4 -> S0. (Wait, if S4 -> S0, then 170ns q=0). \nSo 165ns must be S4 -> S4. \n- 165ns: a=1, posedge, S4 -> S4. p=1, q=1. (Matches).\n- 170ns: a=0, posedge, S4 -> S4. p=0, q=1. (Matches).\n- 175ns: a=1, negedge, S4 -> S0. p=0, q=0. (Matches!).\n\nFinal State Machine:\n- Posedge: S0->S1 (a=1), S1->S2 (a=1), S2->S3 (a=1), S3->S4 (a=0), S4->S4 (a=1/0?), S4->S0 (a=1 at negedge).\n- Negedge: S4->S0 (a=1).\n\nWait, let's just use a single `always @(posedge clock, negedge clock)` and see.\n- 